{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01NJbpVSx6Rb22kzEu6biHuK","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have all the information needed for a complete audit. Let me summarize the findings:\n\n1. **Worker replica count**: ray-worker has `replicas: 1`\n2. **Image versions**: Both ray-head and ray-worker use `rayproject/ray:2.9.0`\n3. **Resource requests/limits**: Both deployments have `resources: {}` — no requests or limits set\n4. **Services**: Only `ray-head` ClusterIP service exists, exposing port 6379 (GCS). No dashboard service.\n5. **ray-head specific config**:\n   - `--include-dashboard=false` — dashboard is explicitly DISABLED\n   - `--num-cpus=0` — head node is configured for scheduling only\n6. **ray-worker specific config**:\n   - `--num-cpus=1` — each worker has 1 CPU available\n   - connects to `ray-head:6379`\n7. **ConfigMaps**: Only the system default `kube-root-ca.crt` exists, no application ConfigMaps\n\nNow I'm comparing this setup against typical Ray cluster defaults to identify deviations. The single worker replica is minimal, and the image version is pinned to 2.9.0 rather than using latest.\n\nLooking at the key differences: the dashboard is explicitly disabled rather than enabled by default, there are no resource requests or limits defined on either deployment which creates a compliance gap, the head node is intentionally set to zero CPUs for scheduler-only operation, and the service only exposes the GCS port while omitting the dashboard and client ports. The configuration uses a specific Ray version and has no application-level ConfigMaps.\n\nNow I'll document these findings in a ConfigMap.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2610,"cache_read_input_tokens":30521,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2610},"output_tokens":19,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"83102c9c-ae78-4d9d-ba7d-0445a7ea7953","uuid":"9c80df41-b7cd-43b3-884d-a1d683a97137","request_id":"req_011CcPyRqwZBTxVeb8o32TWD"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01NJbpVSx6Rb22kzEu6biHuK","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have all the data needed. Now I'll compose the audit report and create the ConfigMap."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2610,"cache_read_input_tokens":30521,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2610},"output_tokens":19,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"83102c9c-ae78-4d9d-ba7d-0445a7ea7953","uuid":"45a41d93-c7cf-4c71-97b9-5f58e5fda5d6","request_id":"req_011CcPyRqwZBTxVeb8o32TWD"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01NJbpVSx6Rb22kzEu6biHuK","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_015qy8h5uXnA3mVaEAhdK2Rw","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"kubectl -n ray create configmap config-audit --from-literal=findings.txt=\"$(cat <<'REPORT'\nRAY CLUSTER CONFIGURATION AUDIT\nNamespace: ray\nAudit Date: 2026-06-25\nAuditor: read-only inspection (no cluster changes made)\n\n================================================================\n1. WORKER REPLICA COUNT\n================================================================\nDeployment : ray-worker\nReplicas   : 1 (spec.replicas = 1, readyReplicas = 1)\nStatus     : 1/1 Ready\n\nDeviation  : Minimal worker count. Default KubeRay / upstream Ray\n             examples typically start with 1 worker, so this matches\n             baseline, but is not scaled up beyond one replica.\n             If higher throughput is required, replicas should be\n             increased and an HPA considered.\n\n================================================================\n2. IMAGE VERSIONS\n================================================================\nray-head   : rayproject/ray:2.9.0\nray-worker : rayproject/ray:2.9.0\n\nDeviation  : Both components run the same pinned version (2.9.0).\n             Using a pinned tag is a good practice (avoids surprise\n             upgrades). Verify this tag is the approved/tested version\n             for this environment before the next change window.\n             Ray 2.9.0 was released in early 2024; check the project\n             release page for security advisories against this version.\n\n================================================================\n3. RESOURCE REQUESTS / LIMITS\n================================================================\nray-head   : resources: {}  (no requests or limits set)\nray-worker : resources: {}  (no requests or limits set)\n\nDeviation  : NEITHER deployment sets CPU or memory requests/limits.\n             This is a significant compliance gap:\n             - Without requests, the Kubernetes scheduler cannot make\n               informed placement decisions; pods may land on\n               over-committed nodes.\n             - Without limits, a runaway Ray task can exhaust node\n               resources and starve other workloads.\n             Recommended minimums (tune to workload):\n               ray-head  : requests cpu=500m,memory=1Gi\n                           limits   cpu=1,memory=2Gi\n               ray-worker: requests cpu=1,memory=1Gi\n                           limits   cpu=2,memory=4Gi\n\n================================================================\n4. RAY-HEAD STARTUP FLAGS (non-default)\n================================================================\nCommand: ray start --head\n         --node-ip-address=\"${MY_POD_IP}\"\n         --port=6379\n         --include-dashboard=false   <-- EXPLICITLY DISABLED\n         --num-cpus=0                <-- HEAD IS SCHEDULING-ONLY\n         --block\n\nKey deviations from upstream defaults:\n  --include-dashboard=false : Ray dashboard is disabled.\n    Default is true. Dashboard provides observability (task timeline,\n    actor graph, resource usage). Disabling reduces attack surface but\n    removes runtime visibility. If internal monitoring tools are in\n    place this may be intentional; document the rationale.\n  --num-cpus=0 : Head node advertises 0 CPUs to the scheduler.\n    This is a recommended production pattern — keeps the head node free\n    for cluster-management duties and prevents user tasks from landing\n    on it. Not a compliance issue; document as intentional.\n\n================================================================\n5. SERVICES EXPOSED\n================================================================\nName      : ray-head\nType      : ClusterIP (cluster-internal only)\nClusterIP : 10.96.191.98\nPorts     : 6379/TCP  (name: gcs — GCS server / cluster membership)\nSelector  : app.kubernetes.io/component=head, app.kubernetes.io/name=ray\n\nNo other services found in the ray namespace.\n\nDeviations / Notes:\n  - Dashboard port (8265) is NOT exposed — consistent with\n    --include-dashboard=false in the head startup command.\n  - Ray client port (10001) is NOT exposed — external Python clients\n    cannot connect via ray.init(\"ray://<host>:10001\"). If external\n    client access is needed a separate service must be created.\n  - Service type is ClusterIP (internal only). No NodePort or\n    LoadBalancer exposure — good from a security standpoint.\n  - The GCS port 6379 shares the same default as Redis; ensure network\n    policies restrict access to authorised pods only.\n\n================================================================\n6. CONFIGMAPS\n================================================================\nkube-root-ca.crt : system-injected CA bundle (every namespace)\n\nNo application-level ConfigMaps present.\n\nDeviations  : No Ray-specific ConfigMaps (e.g. custom ray-config,\n              logging config, or environment overrides). If runtime\n              tunables are managed via env vars in the Deployment spec\n              rather than ConfigMaps, that is acceptable but less\n              auditable. Recommend externalising environment config\n              into a ConfigMap for change-tracking visibility.\n\n================================================================\n7. SUMMARY OF DEVIATIONS FROM BASELINE\n================================================================\n| Component     | Parameter              | Observed          | Baseline/Expected         | Severity |\n|---------------|------------------------|-------------------|---------------------------|----------|\n| ray-head      | resources.requests     | (none)            | cpu/memory set            | HIGH     |\n| ray-head      | resources.limits       | (none)            | cpu/memory set            | HIGH     |\n| ray-worker    | resources.requests     | (none)            | cpu/memory set            | HIGH     |\n| ray-worker    | resources.limits       | (none)            | cpu/memory set            | HIGH     |\n| ray-head      | --include-dashboard    | false             | true (upstream default)   | LOW      |\n| ray-head      | --num-cpus             | 0                 | (node capacity)           | INFO     |\n| ray-worker    | replicas               | 1                 | (workload-dependent)      | INFO     |\n| ray-head svc  | dashboard port (8265)  | not exposed       | exposed if dashboard on   | INFO     |\n| ray-head svc  | client port (10001)    | not exposed       | exposed if clients needed | INFO     |\n| Namespace     | application ConfigMaps | none              | expected for tunables     | LOW      |\n\n================================================================\n8. COMPLIANCE RECOMMENDATIONS\n================================================================\n[CRITICAL] Set CPU and memory requests AND limits on both ray-head\n           and ray-worker containers before any further scaling.\n           Without these, SLA guarantees are not enforceable and\n           the cluster poses a noisy-neighbour risk.\n\n[MEDIUM]   Add a NetworkPolicy in the ray namespace to restrict\n           who can reach port 6379 (GCS). Currently any pod in\n           the cluster can join the Ray cluster.\n\n[LOW]      Decide and document whether --include-dashboard=false\n           is intentional policy or an oversight. If intentional,\n           add it to the cluster's architecture decision record.\n\n[LOW]      Externalise runtime environment variables into a\n           ConfigMap so changes are visible in git/audit logs.\n\n[INFO]     Image rayproject/ray:2.9.0 is pinned — verify it is\n           free of known CVEs before the next change window and\n           confirm it matches the approved image list.\n\n================================================================\nEND OF AUDIT REPORT\n================================================================\nREPORT\n)\" 2>&1","description":"Create config-audit ConfigMap with findings.txt"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2610,"cache_read_input_tokens":30521,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2610},"output_tokens":19,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"83102c9c-ae78-4d9d-ba7d-0445a7ea7953","uuid":"686123eb-838f-4562-a594-5ed4d192e4d9","request_id":"req_011CcPyRqwZBTxVeb8o32TWD"}
